<script>
  (function() {
    // Core Data with accurate 2025 FY Customer Deposits
    const banks = [
      { id: "zenith", name: "Zenith Bank", volume: 104.14, revenue: 169.18, deposits: 24.33 },
      { id: "uba", name: "UBA", volume: 51.65, revenue: 461.94, deposits: 23.95 },
      { id: "first", name: "First Bank", volume: 58.00, revenue: 167.92, deposits: 18.89 }, 
      { id: "gtco", name: "GTCO", volume: 72.40, revenue: 121.29, deposits: 12.55 }
    ];

    // Auto-calculate Totals for Market Share
    const totals = {
      volume: banks.reduce((sum, b) => sum + b.volume, 0),
      revenue: banks.reduce((sum, b) => sum + b.revenue, 0),
      deposits: banks.reduce((sum, b) => sum + b.deposits, 0)
    };

    const config = {
      volume: {
        prefix: '₦', suffix: ' Trillion', shortSuffix: 'T',
        insight: "<strong>The Macro View:</strong> Together, these four banks processed a staggering <strong>₦286 trillion</strong> on mobile in 2025, proving traditional infrastructure is back online."
      },
      revenue: {
        prefix: '₦', suffix: ' Billion', shortSuffix: 'B',
        insight: "<strong>The Macro View:</strong> These four banks extracted over <strong>₦920 billion</strong> in digital revenue in 2025, but the spoils are heavily skewed toward one player."
      },
      deposits: {
        prefix: '₦', suffix: ' Trillion', shortSuffix: 'T',
        insight: "<strong>The Macro View:</strong> This is the moat. Fintechs may win on everyday transfer frequency, but the Big Four hold nearly <strong>₦80 trillion</strong> in deposits."
      }
    };

    // Attach to global scope for button clicks
    window.tcRenderDashboard = function(metric) {
      // 1. Update UI Tabs
      document.querySelectorAll('.tc-tab-btn').forEach(btn => {
        btn.classList.remove('active');
        if(btn.innerText.toLowerCase().includes(metric.substring(0,4))) {
          btn.classList.add('active');
        }
      });

      // 2. Update Macro Insight
      document.getElementById('tc-main-insight').innerHTML = config[metric].insight;

      // 3. Sort Data
      const sortedBanks = [...banks].sort((a, b) => b[metric] - a[metric]);
      const maxVal = sortedBanks[0][metric]; // Highest value sets the 100% bar width
      const totalVal = totals[metric];

      // 4. Render Cards
      const chartArea = document.getElementById('tc-chart-area');
      chartArea.innerHTML = '';

      sortedBanks.forEach((bank, index) => {
        const barWidth = (bank[metric] / maxVal) * 100;
        const marketShare = ((bank[metric] / totalVal) * 100).toFixed(1);
        const formattedValue = `${config[metric].prefix}${bank[metric].toFixed(2)}${config[metric].shortSuffix}`;
        
        const card = document.createElement('div');
        card.className = 'tc-bank-card';
        card.onclick = () => tcToggleCard(card);
        
        card.innerHTML = `
          <div class="tc-bank-header-row">
            <span class="tc-bank-name"><i class="tc-chevron"></i> ${bank.name}</span>
            <span class="tc-bank-val">${formattedValue}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="tc-bar-bg">
            <div class="tc-bar-fill" style="width: 0%"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tc-drawer">
            <div class="tc-insight-pill">
              <strong>Market Share:</strong> ${bank.name} controls <strong>${marketShare}%</strong> of the Big Four's total ${metric.toLowerCase()} pool.
            </div>
          </div>
        `;
        
        chartArea.appendChild(card);
        
        // Animate Bars after a tiny delay
        setTimeout(() => {
          card.querySelector('.tc-bar-fill').style.width = barWidth + '%';
        }, 50 + (index * 100));
      });
    };

    // Toggle logic for Accordion
    window.tcToggleCard = function(clickedCard) {
      const allCards = document.querySelectorAll('.tc-bank-card');
      
      // If clicking the already expanded card, close it
      if (clickedCard.classList.contains('expanded')) {
        clickedCard.classList.remove('expanded');
        return;
      }
      
      // Close all others and open the clicked one
      allCards.forEach(c => c.classList.remove('expanded'));
      clickedCard.classList.add('expanded');
    };

    // Initialize
    setTimeout(() => { tcRenderDashboard('volume'); }, 100);
  })();
</script>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>What this means for customers</strong></h2>



<p>For customers, this shift reduces the need to juggle between bank apps and fintech platforms for everyday transfers. Where users once deposited lump amounts in banks but relied on fintechs for everyday transfers, improving reliability on bank apps means more transactions can happen in one place.</p>



<p>Also, as banks close the gap on speed and uptime, <a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/04/27/why-transfers-above-%E2%82%A610000-will-cost-%E2%82%A660/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">pricing may become the main differentiator</a>. Ultimately, transfers will become less about which app works and more about which app offers the best value or additional services, from credit to savings and rewards.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>What this means for fintechs</strong></h2>



<p>For fintechs, the advantage that drove their growth, speed, and reliability is starting to wane.</p>



<p>As banks fix their apps and reduce failures, fintechs risk losing the high-frequency transactions that made them indispensable for everyday payments.&nbsp;</p>



<p>That puts pressure on their core model, which depends on volume and engagement, even if users still keep most of their money in traditional banks.</p>



<p><a href="https://doclib.ngxgroup.com/Financial_NewsDocs/46482_GUARANTY_TRUST_HOLDING_COMPANY_PLC-_QUARTER_5_-_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT_FOR_2025_FINANCIAL_STATEMENTS_MARCH_2026.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">GTCO</a>,<a href="https://first-holdco.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/FIRST_HOLDCO_PLC-_YEAR_END_-_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT_FOR_2025_FINANCIAL_STATEMENTS.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"> First Bank</a>,<a href="https://doclib.ngxgroup.com/Financial_NewsDocs/46757_UNITED_BANK_FOR_AFRICA_PLC-_QUARTER_5_-_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT_FOR_2025_FINANCIAL_STATEMENTS_APRIL_2026.pdf"> </a><a href="https://doclib.ngxgroup.com/Financial_NewsDocs/46757_UNITED_BANK_FOR_AFRICA_PLC-_QUARTER_5_-_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT_FOR_2025_FINANCIAL_STATEMENTS_APRIL_2026.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">UBA</a>, and<a href="https://www.zenithbank.com/media/z3dmhjbt/zenith-bank-group-2025-fye-full-financial-statement.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"> Zenith Bank</a> had ₦79.72 trillion ($57.98 billion) in customer deposits at the end of 2025.</p>



<p>The next phase for fintech could be less about acquiring users and more about keeping them. To do that, fintechs may need to deepen trust through better dispute resolution, stronger customer support, and, in some cases, physical or hybrid touchpoints.&nbsp;</p>



<p>At the same time, regulation is beginning to close the structural gap. With the <a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/01/29/kuda-mfb-national-licence-upgrade/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">CBN</a> pushing leading fintechs toward National Microfinance Bank licences, they are being drawn into the same realities as banks, including higher compliance costs, physical presence, and tighter oversight.</p>



<p>As speed becomes standard, fintechs will have to compete less on execution and more on what they can build on top of payments, from credit to financial services, while managing a cost structure that may increasingly start to look like that of the institutions they once disrupted<strong>.</strong><br></p>



<p><strong><em>Note: exchange rate used: ₦1,374.94/$</em></strong></p>



<p></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>StanChart Kenya cuts staff below 1,000 in 11th year of restructuring</title>
		<link>https://techcabal.com/2026/05/04/stanchart-kenya-cuts-staff-below-1000-in-11th-year-of-restructuring/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Adonijah Ndege]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 04 May 2026 08:19:25 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Banking]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[StanChart Kenya]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Standard Chartered Kenya]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://techcabal.com/?p=187198</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[ The decline extends a retrenchment that has seen headcount more than halve from a peak of 2,048 in 2014.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Standard Chartered Kenya (StanChart), the country&#8217;s eighth-largest bank by assets, has reduced its workforce to fewer than 1,000 employees, capping 11 consecutive years of job cuts as the lender automates its banking operations across East Africa&#8217;s largest economy.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The lender employed 942 people at the end of 2025, down from 1,001 a year earlier, <a href="https://www.sc.com/en/investors/financial-results/annual-report/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">according to its latest annual report.</a> The decline extends a retrenchment that has seen headcount more than halve from <a href="https://nation.africa/kenya/business/stanchart-sends-home-285-staff--45812" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">a peak of 2,048 in 2014.</a></p>



<p>Redundancy costs for the latest financial year totalled KES 112.27 million ($870,000), a sharp fall from KES 580.1 million ($4.4 million) in 2024, suggesting a deceleration in the pace of layoffs even as restructuring continues. Over the past decade, the bank has spent KES 4.71 billion on workforce reduction.</p>



<p>The sustained downsizing reflects a pivot <a href="https://kenyanwallstreet.com/stanchart-bank-to-cut-down-global-network" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">from brick-and-mortar branches and retail banking towards wealth management</a>, corporate lending, and digital-first service delivery,  a transition accelerated by the Covid-19 pandemic but now part of the bank&#8217;s operations.</p>



<p>StanChart has invested more than <a href="https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/bd/corporate/companies/stanchart-slashes-jobs-by-half-in-10-years-amid-automation-5066634" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">KES 14 billion ($108.4 million) in digital capabilities over five years,</a> automating services and moving customers towards mobile and online platforms. The bank operated 42 branches in 2016, but that number fell to fewer than 25 in 2025.</p>



<p>Despite the cuts, StanChart&#8217;s total staff costs rose to KES 11.4 billion ($88.2 million) in 2025, up from KES 9.3 billion a year earlier, suggesting the bank is retaining fewer but highly skilled and specialised employees, particularly in technology, risk, and relationship management roles serving affluent and corporate clients.</p>



<p>While digital transactions now account for most customer interactions across Kenya&#8217;s financial system, some large lenders, such as <a href="https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/bd/corporate/industry/kenyan-banks-lead-regional-peers-with-150-new-branches-3843886" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">KCB Group, Equity Group, and Co-operative Bank of Kenya,</a> have expanded their workforces in recent years.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Foot traffic in banking halls has declined sharply, weakening the commercial case for maintaining large branch networks and the back-office teams that support them—particularly for lenders like StanChart, whose affluent clientele has largely migrated to digital channels.</p>



<p></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
