<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Day 1000: Pivots and the pivot hell</strong></h2>



<p>Insight7&#8217;s first pivot came in 2024.&nbsp;</p>



<p>After months of trying to convince product teams to act on a problem they acknowledged but would not prioritise, Odubanjo and his team were forced to redirect their focus when a representative from an unnamed market research company, who was already working closely with quantitative data, requested the solution.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;We did more research, and we understood that there was this whole segment of people who were doing a lot of market research that required qualitative analysis,&#8221; he said. &#8220;So we just pivoted at that point; focused the same product on a new market, and created a lot of content around it. We started to see traction.&#8221;</p>



<p>By the end of 2024, Odubanjo said that Insight7 had generated 10x its revenue from the previous year.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;We were still passionate about helping businesses transform how they leverage data to make decisions and serve their customers better,” he said. “But if we didn&#8217;t pivot, we wouldn&#8217;t exist now.&#8221;</p>



<p>That newfound stability only lasted for less than a year.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>With the increasing popularity of general-purpose AI tools like Claude, ChatGPT, and Copilot, and the products offering similar analytics capabilities, sometimes for free, competition intensified for Insight7. So came the startup&#8217;s second pivot.</p>



<p>This time, it began to reshape its product to focus on analysing customer service calls and using the data to train employees. That idea came as a request from one of its users.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;We felt we could use the same underlying platform to build a new user experience for that,&#8221; Odubanjo said.&nbsp;</p>



<p>He explained that the demand for the new version of Insight7 outpaced the old, and by the end of 2025, revenue had tripled. “It’s been a story of a lot of pivots, he said.</p>



<p>Odubanjo described those transition periods as “pivot hell,” a phase where a product is not fully working and its next direction is unclear.&nbsp;</p>



<p>“It&#8217;s challenging, but also very exciting because we have the conviction that our customers need our current products,” he said.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Insight7&#8217;s current iteration reflects these pivots.&nbsp;</p>



<p>What started as a tool for analysing interviews for product teams has evolved into a platform with features including call performance scorecards from conversations with customers, AI coaching and roleplay for practising real conversation scenarios, a live AI assistant that provides real-time guidance during conversations, and a knowledge base with evidence tracking.</p>



<p>Insight7 operates on a Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) tiered subscription model, with customers paying monthly or annually based on usage, features, and team size. Subscription ranges from $0-$250 monthly.</p>



<p>The startup has also expanded its business model to cater to individual customers rather than businesses by launching a consumer-facing app, Insight7 AI Coach for communication, in April.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The app was designed to help individuals improve communication skills across interviews, the workplace and personal conversations, and is priced at $14.99 monthly.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Insight7 competes with a set of AI tools that offer parts of its functionality, including Observe.AI, Quantified AI, and Document360.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;Our moat is compounding intelligence, meaning every interaction makes our customers smarter over time,&#8221; Odubanjo said.</p>



<p>Insight7 is also looking to deepen its presence in Nigeria, where its founders and early network are rooted, while continuing to serve its global customers, according to Odubanjo.</p>



<p>When asked if there will be more pivots for Insight7 in the future, he said, “You have got to keep pivoting… You have got to choose: do you want to die or do you want to be alive?”</p>
